quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Frameworks&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/frameworks&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:146,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Laravel Queue Mastery&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nIn this series, join Mohamed Said, from the Laravel core team, as he reviews the ins and outs of how to use Laravel&#39;s high-performance queue system to run any potentially long-running task asynchronously. You&#39;ll begin by dispatching your first job, and slowly work your way up to more complex configurations and deployment techniques.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/laravel-queue-mastery&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nIn this series, join Mohamed Said, from the Laravel core team, as he reviews the ins and outs of how to use Laravel&#39;s high-performance queue system to run any potentially long-running task asynchronously. You&#39;ll begin by dispatching your first job, and slowly work your way up to more complex configurations and deployment techniques.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/queue-mastery.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/laravel-queue-mastery.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/queue-mastery.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;laravel-queue-mastery&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:12,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 41m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:145,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Beginning TypeScript&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nAs the complexity and scale of our apps forever increases, &lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/www.typescriptlang.org\/\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;TypeScript&lt;\/a&gt; has risen in popularity as people seek the reassurances of type safety in their applications. Major frameworks such as Vue have rewritten their entire code bases in TypeScript. \r\n&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\nNonetheless, there is a cost associated with adopting it. Teams must learn how to use a new set of tooling, think about their code in a different way, and learn concepts that may be foreign to them. This series aims to ease the transition to TypeScript. It assumes basic knowledge of JavaScript but otherwise serves as an introduction to the most common types that will enable you to build real applications in TypeScript.&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/beginning-typescript&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nAs the complexity and scale of our apps forever increases, TypeScript has risen in popularity as people seek the reassurances of type safety in their applications. Major frameworks such as Vue have rewritten their entire code bases in TypeScript. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNonetheless, there is a cost associated with adopting it. Teams must learn how to use a new set of tooling, think about their code in a different way, and learn concepts that may be foreign to them. This series aims to ease the transition to TypeScript. It assumes basic knowledge of JavaScript but otherwise serves as an introduction to the most common types that will enable you to build real applications in TypeScript.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/typescript-for-beginners.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/beginning-typescript.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/typescript-for-beginners.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;beginning-typescript&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:11,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;TypeScript 4.3&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 32m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Languages&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/languages&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:144,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Developer Practice&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nLike any other discipline, programmers must dedicate a certain portion of their time to improving their workflow and skillset. This might include working along with a programming video, or practicing a coding kata, or reviewing a new tool. In this series, one topic per episode, we&#39;ll review examples of what this developer practice looks like. \r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/development-workflow&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nLike any other discipline, programmers must dedicate a certain portion of their time to improving their workflow and skillset. This might include working along with a programming video, or practicing a coding kata, or reviewing a new tool. In this series, one topic per episode, we&#39;ll review examples of what this developer practice looks like. \r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/developer-practice.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/development-workflow.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/developer-practice.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;development-workflow&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:1,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:null,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:0,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;19m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:143,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Build a Voting App&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nIn this workshop, we\u2019ll build a voting app, similar to UserVoice, that allows you to create ideas, vote and comment on them, sort and filter the results, and even administer the site. We\u2019ll start from scratch and work through the entire process, including implementing the design, working on all of the features, testing our code, and more. &lt;\/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;We\u2019ll be making use of the TALL (Tailwind, Alpine, Livewire, Laravel) stack in this particular series.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/build-a-voting-app&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nIn this workshop, we\u2019ll build a voting app, similar to UserVoice, that allows you to create ideas, vote and comment on them, sort and filter the results, and even administer the site. We\u2019ll start from scratch and work through the entire process, including implementing the design, working on all of the features, testing our code, and more. \r\n\r\nWe\u2019ll be making use of the TALL (Tailwind, Alpine, Livewire, Laravel) stack in this particular series.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/build-a-voting-app.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/build-a-voting-app.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/build-a-voting-app.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;build-a-voting-app&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:67,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8, Tailwind 2, Livewire 2&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;18h 19m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:142,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8 From Scratch&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nWe don&#39;t learn tools for the sake of learning tools. Instead, we learn them because they help us accomplish a particular goal. With that in mind, in this series, we&#39;ll use the common desire for a blog - with categories, tags, comments, email notifications, and more - as our goal. Laravel will be the tool that helps us get there. Each lesson, geared toward newcomers to Laravel, will provide instructions and techniques that will get you to the finish line. \r\n&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This version of our popular Laravel From Scratch series was recorded in 2021, and uses Laravel 8.&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/laravel-8-from-scratch&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nWe don&#39;t learn tools for the sake of learning tools. Instead, we learn them because they help us accomplish a particular goal. With that in mind, in this series, we&#39;ll use the common desire for a blog - with categories, tags, comments, email notifications, and more - as our goal. Laravel will be the tool that helps us get there. Each lesson, geared toward newcomers to Laravel, will provide instructions and techniques that will get you to the finish line. \r\n\r\nThis version of our popular Laravel From Scratch series was recorded in 2021, and uses Laravel 8.&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/laravel-from-scratch-2021.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/laravel-8-from-scratch.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/laravel-from-scratch-2021.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;laravel-8-from-scratch&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:61,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:0,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;8h 9m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Frameworks&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/frameworks&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:141,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;HTML and CSS Workshop&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nIf you&#39;d like to come along for the ride, I need to write the HTML and CSS for a blog design that we&#39;ll be using as part of an upcoming series. We&#39;ll be entirely focused on HTML and CSS (using Tailwind), exclusively. This will give us plenty of opportunities to discuss common gotchas and techniques. We&#39;ll even run into a roadblock here and there.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/html-and-css-workshop&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nIf you&#39;d like to come along for the ride, I need to write the HTML and CSS for a blog design that we&#39;ll be using as part of an upcoming series. We&#39;ll be entirely focused on HTML and CSS (using Tailwind), exclusively. This will give us plenty of opportunities to discuss common gotchas and techniques. We&#39;ll even run into a roadblock here and there.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/html-and-css-workflow.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/html-and-css-workshop.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/html-and-css-workflow.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;html-and-css-workshop&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:5,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Tailwind 2&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 21m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Languages&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/languages&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:140,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Learn Inertia With Jeffrey&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\n&lt;a target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;https:\/\/inertiajs.com\&quot;&gt;Inertia.js&lt;\/a&gt; allows you to build single-page applications, while still allowing Laravel to be responsible for routing, controllers, authorization, policies, and more. Think of it like the glue that connects a server-side framework like Laravel, to a client-side framework like Vue.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Despite all the hype, I&#39;m only just now taking a first look at all that Inertia has to offer. If you&#39;re in the same position, why don&#39;t you come along and we&#39;ll learn it together? &lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/learn-inertia-with-jeffrey&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nInertia.js allows you to build single-page applications, while still allowing Laravel to be responsible for routing, controllers, authorization, policies, and more. Think of it like the glue that connects a server-side framework like Laravel, to a client-side framework like Vue.\r\n\r\nDespite all the hype, I&#39;m only just now taking a first look at all that Inertia has to offer. If you&#39;re in the same position, why don&#39;t you come along and we&#39;ll learn it together? &quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/learn-inertia-with-me.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/learn-inertia-with-jeffrey.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/learn-inertia-with-me.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;learn-inertia-with-jeffrey&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:11,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8, Inertia 0.8&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 30m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Frameworks&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/frameworks&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:139,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Modals with the TALL Stack&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nFor such a simple concept, modals can often be tricky to implement. Where exactly do we place them? Where should the event listeners to toggle their display be stored? And how to we make them dynamic? In this series, one piece at a time, we&#39;ll discuss everything you need to know about modals within the TALL (Tailwind, Alpine, Laravel, Livewire) stack.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/modals-with-the-tall-stack&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nFor such a simple concept, modals can often be tricky to implement. Where exactly do we place them? Where should the event listeners to toggle their display be stored? And how to we make them dynamic? In this series, one piece at a time, we&#39;ll discuss everything you need to know about modals within the TALL (Tailwind, Alpine, Laravel, Livewire) stack.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/modals-and-the-tall-stack.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/modals-with-the-tall-stack.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/modals-and-the-tall-stack.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;modals-with-the-tall-stack&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:9,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel 8, Livewire 2, Alpine 2, Tailwind 2&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 17m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:138,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How to Read Code: Season 2&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s time for a new entry in our \&quot;&lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/series\/how-to-read-code\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;How to Read Code&lt;\/a&gt;\&quot; series. This season, we&#39;ll dive into the &lt;a href=\&quot;http:\/\/github.com\/laravel\/breeze\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;Laravel Breeze&lt;\/a&gt; source code, taking every opportunity to peek behind the scenes to learn how and why it was constructed in this way.&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;While it&#39;s often unnecessary to review the underlying code of the packages and tools you use, that doesn&#39;t mean you won&#39;t benefit from doing so. If you want to become a better programmer, you must learn, read, and write a lot of code. This series focuses on the reading.&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/how-to-read-code-season-2&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;It&#39;s time for a new entry in our \&quot;How to Read Code\&quot; series. This season, we&#39;ll dive into the Laravel Breeze source code, taking every opportunity to peek behind the scenes to learn how and why it was constructed in this way.\r\nWhile it&#39;s often unnecessary to review the underlying code of the packages and tools you use, that doesn&#39;t mean you won&#39;t benefit from doing so. If you want to become a better programmer, you must learn, read, and write a lot of code. This series focuses on the reading.&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/how-to-read-code-season-2.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/how-to-read-code-season-2.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/how-to-read-code-season-2.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;how-to-read-code-season-2&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:8,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Laravel Breeze 1&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 19m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:137,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Set Up a Mac for Development From Scratch&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nAs web developers, we use a wealth of software and tools to get our work done. Some are obvious, such as code editors, IDEs and terminals, while others offer minor optimizations to our workflows. In this series, we\u2019ll go over all the software and tools that I personally use for web development, as well as my personal settings for each. I\u2019ve picked up countless tips from watching other developers&#39; workflows over the years, and I hope do the same for you in this series.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/setup-a-mac-for-development-from-scratch&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nAs web developers, we use a wealth of software and tools to get our work done. Some are obvious, such as code editors, IDEs and terminals, while others offer minor optimizations to our workflows. In this series, we\u2019ll go over all the software and tools that I personally use for web development, as well as my personal settings for each. I\u2019ve picked up countless tips from watching other developers&#39; workflows over the years, and I hope do the same for you in this series.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/setup-a-mac-for-development-from-scratch.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/setup-a-mac-for-development-from-scratch.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/setup-a-mac-for-development-from-scratch.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;setup-a-mac-for-development-from-scratch&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:7,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:null,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 23m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Tooling&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/tooling&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:136,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Pull Up a Seat: Season 1&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;Real-life programming isn&#39;t always glamorous. You&#39;re not always launching fancy new interactive features backed by weeks of marketing and hype. In fact, that&#39;s rarely the case. Instead, much of the time, we work on boring fixes and general maintenance of packages and tools that, frankly, not many people use. This is the reality.&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;In that spirit, for season one of our new \&quot;Pull Up a Seat\&quot; series, come along as I work on extending the API for my &lt;code&gt;laracasts\/cypress&lt;\/code&gt; package. We&#39;ll cover everything from the initial tinkering, all the way up to tagging a new release.&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/pull-a-seat-season-1&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;Real-life programming isn&#39;t always glamorous. You&#39;re not always launching fancy new interactive features backed by weeks of marketing and hype. In fact, that&#39;s rarely the case. Instead, much of the time, we work on boring fixes and general maintenance of packages and tools that, frankly, not many people use. This is the reality.\r\n\r\nIn that spirit, for season one of our new \&quot;Pull Up a Seat\&quot; series, come along as I work on extending the API for my laracasts\/cypress package. We&#39;ll cover everything from the initial tinkering, all the way up to tagging a new release.&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/pull-up-a-seat.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/pull-a-seat-season-1.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/pull-up-a-seat.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;pull-a-seat-season-1&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:7,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:null,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;51m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Techniques&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/techniques&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:135,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Laravel Authentication (Breeze, Jetstream, Fortify)&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nLaravel offers several options for &lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laravel.com\/docs\/authentication\&quot;&gt;Authentication&lt;\/a&gt; in your applications. If you&#39;d prefer a head start, you might reach for one of the available first-party packages that provide robust, modern scaffolding for your authentication layer. For example, &lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laravel.com\/docs\/8.x\/starter-kits#laravel-breeze\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;Laravel Breeze&lt;\/a&gt; is an excellent choice to get up and running quickly. If you require additional features, &lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laravel.com\/docs\/8.x\/starter-kits#laravel-jetstream\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;Laravel Jetstream&lt;\/a&gt; offers two-factor auth, API tokens and team management. If you&#39;d instead prefer to use your own front-end stack, you might consider &lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laravel.com\/docs\/8.x\/fortify\&quot;&gt;Laravel Fortify&lt;\/a&gt; as the backend implementation.&lt;\/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt; In this series, we&#39;ll review how to use and customize these packages in order to fit the authentication needs of your application.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/laravel-authentication-options&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nLaravel offers several options for Authentication in your applications. If you&#39;d prefer a head start, you might reach for one of the available first-party packages that provide robust, modern scaffolding for your authentication layer. For example, Laravel Breeze is an excellent choice to get up and running quickly. If you require additional features, Laravel Jetstream offers two-factor auth, API tokens and team management. If you&#39;d instead prefer to use your own front-end stack, you might consider Laravel Fortify as the backend implementation.\r\n\r\n In this series, we&#39;ll review how to use and customize these packages in order to fit the authentication needs of your application.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/laravel-authentication.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/laravel-authentication-options.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/laravel-authentication.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;laravel-authentication-options&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:20,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:null,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;3h 25m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Frameworks&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/frameworks&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:134,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;PHP Testing Jargon&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\nThere&#39;s no two ways about it: terminology in the testing world is incredibly overwhelming. Mocks, stubs, and dummies oh my! &lt;\/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let&#39;s see if we can cut through the noise. Come along as, bit by bit, we break all of these confusing concepts down into something you can easily understand and implement within your own projects.\r\n\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/php-testing-jargon&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nThere&#39;s no two ways about it: terminology in the testing world is incredibly overwhelming. Mocks, stubs, and dummies oh my! \r\nLet&#39;s see if we can cut through the noise. Come along as, bit by bit, we break all of these confusing concepts down into something you can easily understand and implement within your own projects.\r\n\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/testing-jargon-2.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/php-testing-jargon.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/testing-jargon-2.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;php-testing-jargon&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:11,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;PHPUnit 9.5&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:0,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;1h 48m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Testing&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/testing&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:true,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}}],[{&quot;id&quot;:133,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Browser Testing With Laravel Dusk&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\&quot;https:\/\/laravel.com\/docs\/8.x\/dusk#introduction\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;Laravel Dusk&lt;\/a&gt; provides an expressive testing API and browser automation for your apps. In terms of testing, it provides the closest thing to an actual user interacting with your application in a browser.  These tests are typically referred to as end to end tests or browser tests. In this series, we\u2019ll prepare a series of Dusk tests for a standard blog application.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;\/series\/browser-testing-with-laravel-dusk&quot;,&quot;strippedBody&quot;:&quot;\r\nLaravel Dusk provides an expressive testing API and browser automation for your apps. In terms of testing, it provides the closest thing to an actual user interacting with your application in a browser.  These tests are typically referred to as end to end tests or browser tests. In this series, we\u2019ll prepare a series of Dusk tests for a standard blog application.\r\n&quot;,&quot;thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/learn-laravel-dusk.png&quot;,&quot;large_thumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/social-cards\/browser-testing-with-laravel-dusk.png&quot;,&quot;svgThumbnail&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.s3.amazonaws.com\/series\/thumbnails\/svg\/learn-laravel-dusk.svg&quot;,&quot;slug&quot;:&quot;browser-testing-with-laravel-dusk&quot;,&quot;episodeCount&quot;:4,&quot;difficultyLevel&quot;:&quot;Intermediate&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;Dusk v6&quot;,&quot;version_notes&quot;:null,&quot;complete&quot;:1,&quot;archived&quot;:0,&quot;runTime&quot;:&quot;48m&quot;,&quot;taxonomy&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Testing&quot;,&quot;path&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/laracasts.com\/browse\/testing&quot;},&quot;hasChapters&quot;:false,&quot;viewingStatus&quot;:{&quot;isWatchingLater&quot;:null},&quot;progress&quot;:{&quot;started&quot;:false,&quot;completionPercentage&quot;:0,&quot;episodesCompleted&quot;:0,&quot;completed&quot;:false,&quot;nextEpisodePosition&quot;:1}},{&quot;id&quot;:132,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Billing With Laravel Cashier&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;&lt;p&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\&quot;http:\/\/github.com\/laravel\/cashier-stripe\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;&gt;Laravel Cashier&lt;\/a&gt; provides an expressive, fluent interface to Stripe&#39;s (and Paddle&#39;s) subscription billing services. In this series, we\u2019ll take a look at the features of Cashier that will allow you to create the billing portion of a subscription-based SAAS app, including subscribing users to plans, authorizing with middleware, single charges, and invoices.\r\n&lt;\/p&gt;&qu